#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:10
msgid "Parametrizing fixtures and test functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:12
msgid "pytest supports test parametrization in several well-integrated ways:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:14
msgid ""
":py:func:`pytest.fixture` allows to define :ref:`parametrization at the "
"level of fixture functions <fixture-parametrize>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:17
msgid ""
"`@pytest.mark.parametrize`_ allows to define parametrization at the function "
"or class level, provides multiple argument/fixture sets for a particular "
"test function or class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:21
msgid ""
"`pytest_generate_tests`_ enables implementing your own custom dynamic "
"parametrization scheme or extensions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:29
msgid "``@pytest.mark.parametrize``: parametrizing test functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:34
msgid "Several improvements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:37
msgid ""
"The builtin ``pytest.mark.parametrize`` decorator enables parametrization of "
"arguments for a test function.  Here is a typical example of a test function "
"that implements checking that a certain input leads to an expected output::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:42
msgid ""
"# content of test_expectation.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"test_input,expected\", [\n"
"    (\"3+5\", 8),\n"
"    (\"2+4\", 6),\n"
"    (\"6*9\", 42),\n"
"])\n"
"def test_eval(test_input, expected):\n"
"    assert eval(test_input) == expected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:52
msgid ""
"Here, the ``@parametrize`` decorator defines three different ``(test_input,"
"expected)`` tuples so that the ``test_eval`` function will run three times "
"using them in turn::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:56
msgid ""
"$ py.test\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 3 items\n"
"\n"
"test_expectation.py ..F\n"
"\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_eval[6*9-42] ________\n"
"\n"
"test_input = '6*9', expected = 42\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"test_input,expected\", [\n"
"        (\"3+5\", 8),\n"
"        (\"2+4\", 6),\n"
"        (\"6*9\", 42),\n"
"    ])\n"
"    def test_eval(test_input, expected):\n"
">       assert eval(test_input) == expected\n"
"E       assert 54 == 42\n"
"E        +  where 54 = eval('6*9')\n"
"\n"
"test_expectation.py:8: AssertionError\n"
"======= 1 failed, 2 passed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:82
msgid ""
"As designed in this example, only one pair of input/output values fails the "
"simple test function.  And as usual with test function arguments, you can "
"see the ``input`` and ``output`` values in the traceback."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:86
msgid ""
"Note that you could also use the parametrize marker on a class or a module "
"(see :ref:`mark`) which would invoke several functions with the argument "
"sets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:89
msgid ""
"It is also possible to mark individual test instances within parametrize, "
"for example with the builtin ``mark.xfail``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:92
msgid ""
"# content of test_expectation.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"test_input,expected\", [\n"
"    (\"3+5\", 8),\n"
"    (\"2+4\", 6),\n"
"    pytest.mark.xfail((\"6*9\", 42)),\n"
"])\n"
"def test_eval(test_input, expected):\n"
"    assert eval(test_input) == expected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:102
msgid "Let's run this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:104
msgid ""
"$ py.test\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 3 items\n"
"\n"
"test_expectation.py ..x\n"
"\n"
"======= 2 passed, 1 xfailed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:114
msgid ""
"The one parameter set which caused a failure previously now shows up as an "
"\"xfailed (expected to fail)\" test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:117
msgid ""
"To get all combinations of multiple parametrized arguments you can stack "
"``parametrize`` decorators::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:120
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"x\", [0, 1])\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"y\", [2, 3])\n"
"def test_foo(x, y):\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:126
msgid ""
"This will run the test with the arguments set to x=0/y=2, x=0/y=3, x=1/y=2 "
"and x=1/y=3."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:131
msgid ""
"In versions prior to 2.4 one needed to specify the argument names as a "
"tuple.  This remains valid but the simpler ``\"name1,name2,...\"`` comma-"
"separated-string syntax is now advertised first because it's easier to write "
"and produces less line noise."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:139
msgid "Basic ``pytest_generate_tests`` example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:141
msgid ""
"Sometimes you may want to implement your own parametrization scheme or "
"implement some dynamism for determining the parameters or scope of a "
"fixture.   For this, you can use the ``pytest_generate_tests`` hook which is "
"called when collecting a test function.  Through the passed in ``metafunc`` "
"object you can inspect the requesting test context and, most importantly, "
"you can call ``metafunc.parametrize()`` to cause parametrization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:149
msgid ""
"For example, let's say we want to run a test taking string inputs which we "
"want to set via a new ``pytest`` command line option.  Let's first write a "
"simple test accepting a ``stringinput`` fixture function argument::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:153
msgid ""
"# content of test_strings.py\n"
"\n"
"def test_valid_string(stringinput):\n"
"    assert stringinput.isalpha()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:158
msgid ""
"Now we add a ``conftest.py`` file containing the addition of a command line "
"option and the parametrization of our test function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:161
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_addoption(parser):\n"
"    parser.addoption(\"--stringinput\", action=\"append\", default=[],\n"
"        help=\"list of stringinputs to pass to test functions\")\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_generate_tests(metafunc):\n"
"    if 'stringinput' in metafunc.fixturenames:\n"
"        metafunc.parametrize(\"stringinput\",\n"
"                             metafunc.config.option.stringinput)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:172
msgid "If we now pass two stringinput values, our test will run twice::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:174
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q --stringinput=\"hello\" --stringinput=\"world\" test_strings."
"py\n"
"..\n"
"2 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:178
msgid "Let's also run with a stringinput that will lead to a failing test::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:180
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q --stringinput=\"!\" test_strings.py\n"
"F\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_valid_string[!] ________\n"
"\n"
"stringinput = '!'\n"
"\n"
"    def test_valid_string(stringinput):\n"
">       assert stringinput.isalpha()\n"
"E       assert <built-in method isalpha of str object at 0xdeadbeef>()\n"
"E        +  where <built-in method isalpha of str object at 0xdeadbeef> = "
"'!'.isalpha\n"
"\n"
"test_strings.py:3: AssertionError\n"
"1 failed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:195
msgid "As expected our test function fails."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:197
msgid ""
"If you don't specify a stringinput it will be skipped because ``metafunc."
"parametrize()`` will be called with an empty parameter list::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:201
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q -rs test_strings.py\n"
"s\n"
"======= short test summary info ========\n"
"SKIP [1] test_strings.py:1: got empty parameter set ['stringinput'], "
"function test_valid_string at $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/test_strings.py:1\n"
"1 skipped in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/parametrize.rst:207
msgid ""
"For further examples, you might want to look at :ref:`more parametrization "
"examples <paramexamples>`."
msgstr ""

